feed.title: 410 Gap Road (Native Plants), Riddells Creek
feed.subtitle: The plants described are found on a Trust for Nature covenanted private property of just under 11 acres. The property consists of a large timbered hill with a south facing damp slope and a warmer, drier more north facing section with a rocky hill top. The land is 500 metres above sea level, has winter frosts and occasional snow.

entry.title: Amphibromus spp.
entry.content: ID to genus by Neville Walsh. A few plants growing in and beside our patch of creek (Sandy Creek). Pic shows the distinctive membranous ligule of the Amphibromus genus.

entry.title: Daucus glochidiatus
entry.content: New species record for this collection.

entry.title: Hovea heterophylla
entry.content: One white-flowered plant among many mauve-flowered plants.

entry.title: Cassinia longifolia
entry.content: Lovely pink-bud form of Cassinia longifolia. One seen in Sandy Ck Reserve last week too. I think they end up white-flowered.

entry.title: Solanum laciniatum, Strepera graculina
entry.content: Ate 8-10 fruit. Initially seen perched in tree and thought it was a Grey Currawong (see pic 2). Pic 3 shows tail feather markings confirming it is the Pied Currawong. Probably moulting.

entry.title: Eucalyptus viminalis subsp. viminalis
entry.content: Very old/large Manna Gum opposite 410 Gap Road, Riddells Creek. Large hollow is currently home to nesting Kookaburras. Full of life with Koalas, 2 x possum species and many other birds, animals and insects seen in and around it.
